Qatar has thrown its weight behind the resumption of the peace negations between the Sudan government and the Darfur rebels, media reported. The Kuwaiti state news agency, KUNA Monday reported the Qatari support for the talks, without giving details. The negotiations are aimed at restoring stability and paving the way for the reconstruction of the war-torn western Sudan. The support for the resumption of the talks follows President Omar Bashir's meeting with Qatari envoy Mutlag Al- Qahtani in Khartoum last Sunday . The peace The two sides discussed the peace and development in Darfur. Khartoum and the Darfur rebel movements inked a peace deal in 2011 brokered by Qatar, but it soon faltered. The Darfur conflict started in 2003 and has claimed an estimated 300,000 lives and rendered two million people homeless, according to the UN figures. The indictment President Bashir currently faces a warrant of arrest issued by the International Criminal Court (ICC) in 2009 for war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide committed in Darfur. The African Union has strongly opposed the indictment of President Bashir. AU accuses the Hague-based court of bias against African leaders.   Leader of insurgency says continental union siding with Khartoum President Farmajo is determined to complete the process ahead of schedule. Maria and Consolata Mwakikuti, who were joined at the abdomen, become minor celebrities last year